<div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded"><h3>July&nbsp;2022</h3><div name="1.GoverningTexts" data-unique="1.GoverningTexts"></div><h2>1. Governing Texts</h2><div name="1.1.Legislation" data-unique="1.1.Legislation"></div><h3><a id="column-1" name="column-1"></a>1.1. Legislation</h3><ul><li>Recital 47 and 70 as well as Article 21 of the <a href="https://platform.dataguidance.com/cross-border-charts/general-data-protection-regulation" target="_blank">General Data Protection Regulation (Regulation (EU) 2016/679)</a> ('GDPR')</li><li>Article L1, R10 and R10(4) of the Post and Electronic Communications Code (last amended in 2016) (only available in French <a href="https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichCodeArticle.do;jsessionid=263C4B4D0880E716D662030E6BD9E794.tplgfr41s_1?idArticle=LEGIARTI000032235707&amp;cidTexte=LEGITEXT000006070987&amp;categorieLien=id&amp;dateTexte=" target="_blank">here</a>) ('the Communications Code')</li><li>Article 56 of the Act No. 78-17 of 6 January 1978 on Data Processing, Data Files and Individual Liberties (as amended) (only available in French <a href="https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichTexte.do;jsessionid=263C4B4D0880E716D662030E6BD9E794.tplgfr41s_1?cidTexte=JORFTEXT000000886460&amp;dateTexte=20190621" target="_blank">here</a>) ('the Data Protection Act')</li><li>Articles 226-18 and 226-18-1 of the Penal Code (only available in French <a href="https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/affichCode.do;jsessionid=0C4588BF48EE5C75BD5CCD21F998A05C.tplgfr29s_1?cidTexte=LEGITEXT000006070719&amp;dateTexte=20171120" target="_blank">here</a>)</li></ul><div name="1.2.RegulatoryAuthorityGuidance" data-unique="1.2.RegulatoryAuthorityGuidance"></div><h3>1.2. Regulatory Authority Guidance</h3><p>The <a href="https://www.cnil.fr/professionnel" target="_blank">French data protection authority</a> ('CNIL') has a general mission of informing individuals of their rights according to the GDPR and to the Data Protection Act. CNIL can impose 'cease-and-desist' injunctions on data processing or fines to data controllers or data processors.</p><p>CNIL has issued the following guidance:</p><ul><li>Postal and Telephone Prospecting (only available in French <a href="https://www.cnil.fr/sites/default/files/atoms/files/commerce-donnees_perso_prospection.pdf" target="_blank">here</a>) ('the Postal and Telephone Marketing Guidance');</li><li>Prospecting Through Postal Mail (only available in French <a href="https://www.cnil.fr/fr/la-prospection-commerciale-par-courrier-postal" target="_blank">here</a>) ('the Postal Mail Guidance);</li><li>Prospecting Through Post Q&amp;A (only available in French <a href="https://www.cnil.fr/cnil-direct/question/369?visiteur=part" target="_blank">here</a>) ('the Post Q&amp;As');</li><li>Commercial prospecting by post and telephone (telephone call) (only available in French <a href="https://www.cnil.fr/fr/la-prospection-commerciale-par-courrier-postal-et-par-telephone-appel-telephonique" target="_blank">here</a>) ('the Telemarketing Guidance');</li><li>Guidance on the repurposing of publicly available online data for commercial solicitation purposes&nbsp;(only available in French <a href="https://www.cnil.fr/fr/la-reutilisation-des-donnees-publiquement-accessibles-en-ligne-des-fins-de-demarchage-commercial" target="_blank">here</a>)&nbsp;('the Repurposing Data Guidance'); and</li><li>Referential on the processing of personal data carried out for the purpose of managing commercial activities (only available in French <a href="https://www.legifrance.gouv.fr/cnil/id/CNILTEXT000045543374/" target="_blank">here</a>) ('the Referential').</li></ul><div name="2.Definitions" data-unique="2.Definitions"></div><h2>2. Definitions</h2><p><strong>Post</strong>: Any object intended to be delivered to the address indicated by the sender on the object itself or on its packaging, including in the form of coded geographical coordinates, and presented in the final form in which it must be routed. In particular, postal items includes books, catalogues, newspapers, periodicals, and postal parcels containing goods with or without commercial value. In addition, a postal item cannot exceed two kilograms and contains a written communication on a material medium, excluding books, catalogues, newspapers or periodicals. Direct mail is part of correspondence (Article L1 of the Communications Code).</p><p><strong>Postal marketing</strong>: There is no definition of 'postal marketing' in the law.</p><p><strong>Consent</strong>: The Communications Code does not provide any<strong> </strong>definition of 'consent' specifically applicable to postal marketing. However, the GDPR defines 'consent' as 'any freely given, specific, informed and unambiguous indication of the data subject's wishes by which they, by a statement or by a clear affirmative action, signify agreement to the processing of personal data relating to them' (Article 4 (11) of the GDPR, the Referential).</p><div name="3.ConsentRequirements" data-unique="3.ConsentRequirements"></div><h2>3. Consent Requirements</h2><div name="3.1.B2C" data-unique="3.1.B2C"></div><h3><a id="column-3" name="column-3"></a>3.1. B2C</h3><p>Organisations are not required to obtain the prior consent of the recipient before sending postal marketing in the business to consumer ('B2C') context, as long as at the time of the collection of the individuals' details, they were informed that their details would be used for direct marketing purposes and was given the opportunity to oppose such use in a free and simple way, ideally through the use of a check-box (the Postal Mail Guidance).</p><p>If the organisation collecting the data intends to share it with other organisations, it must grant the individual with specific information, including on the purpose and the categories of recipients. The individual must be allowed to oppose to such use in a free and simple way, including through the use of a checkbox (the Telemarketing Guidance).</p><p>Where the data has not been collected directly from the individual but through a third party, the individual must be given information, at the latest on the first contact with the individual, on the identity of the organisation sending a postal message, of the purpose of the message, and of the means to exercise their rights and the source of the data (the Telemarketing Guidance).</p><p>Organisations are prohibited from sending postal marketing to individuals who have explicitly opted-out from receiving such marketing messages (the Postal Mail Guidance).</p><div name="3.2.B2B" data-unique="3.2.B2B"></div><h3><a id="column-4" name="column-4"></a>3.2. B2B</h3><p>Organisations are not required to obtain prior consent when sending business to business ('B2B') postal marketing to the address of a legal person or to the specific address of an employee of that legal person (opt-out). Postal marketing is possible provided that the person was, at the time of collection of their address:</p><ul><li>informed of its use for marketing purposes; and</li><li>able to oppose to this use in a free and simple way, including through a checkbox.</li></ul><p>The individual must also be informed, if applicable, that the data may be shared with other organisations and about the purposes of this sharing and the categories of recipients.</p><div name="3.3Exceptions" data-unique="3.3Exceptions"></div><h3>3.3 Exceptions</h3><p>The processing of personal data for direct marketing purposes may be regarded as carried out for a legitimate interest (Recital 47 of the GDPR, the Referential) on the condition that the latter is not overridden by the interests or fundamental rights and freedoms of the data subject (Article 6(1)(f) of the GDPR).</p><div name="3.4.AdditionalRequirements" data-unique="3.4.AdditionalRequirements"></div><h3>3.4. Additional Requirements</h3><p>Each message sent to an individual must inform them of the identity of the organisation which is calling.</p><p>Organisations must respect an individual's right to object to receiving postal marketing (Article R10(4) of the Communications Code). Individuals can object at any time, must be able to do so free of charge and cannot be required to provide a reason for opting-out. They can also oppose the transfer of their details to other commercial companies (the Postal and Telephone Marketing Guidance, the Telemarketing Guidance).</p><p><strong>Right to object</strong></p><p>Where personal data are processed for direct marketing purposes, the data subject has the right to object at any time to processing of personal data concerning them for such marketing, which includes profiling (Article 21 of the GDPR).</p><p>The data subject should be able to exercise the right to object whether with regard to initial or further processing, at any time and free of charge, and such right should be explicitly brought to their attention and presented clearly and separately from any other information (Recital 70 of the GDPR). In the case that the organisation to which the individual exercised their right to object has transmitted the data to other organisations, it must inform this organisation immediately of the exercise of this right (the Telemarketing Guidance).</p><p><strong>Children</strong></p><p>Specific protection should be provided with regard to personal data of children for the purposes of marketing or creating personality or user profiles and the collection of personal data with regard to children when using services offered directly to a child (Recital 38 of the GDPR).</p><div name="4.MarketingLists" data-unique="4.MarketingLists"></div><h2>4. Marketing Lists</h2><p>When they intend to scrape publicly available data online, organisations must ensure that the terms of use of the website they intend to scrape data from does not forbid such a collection. Moreover, organisations must ensure to collect the data subjects' consent if the data subjects who made their data public did not reasonably expect to be the subject of marketing by another company. The mere acceptance by an internet user, in a general and non-specific manner, of the terms of use of a service cannot be regarded as a specific consent, even if these terms of use inform the user that they may receive marketing materials by physical or electronic means (the Repurposing Data Guidance).</p><p>The collected data must not excess the minimal requirements, especially concerning special categories of data.</p><p>Organisations transmitting the data must collect this consent, on behalf of the recipients, at the time of the initial collection of the data. To do so, individuals must be informed of the identity of the data controller partners who would use their data for marketing purposes, through an exhaustive list made available directly on or from the collection medium (e.g., by including a hyperlink), as well as the specific purpose of the transmission (the Referential).</p><p>Otherwise, the recipients of the data must collect consent themselves by soliciting the data subjects, which constitutes a processing of personal data operation which must be based on the recipient's documented legitimate interest and cannot itself be considered as a commercial proposition (the Referential).</p><p>Organisations are required to inform in a clear and plain way, at the latest upon the first contact with the data subjects, with all information provided in Article 14 of the GDPR, and namely on the purposes of the processing and the source of the data (the Referential).</p><p>It is prohibited to send postal marketing to an individual by collecting their details on their mailbox or because they appear on various ads. Individuals must have control of their details and organisations must use their details in a transparent way (the Postal and Telephone Marketing Guidance).</p><div name="5.NationalOpt-OutList" data-unique="5.NationalOpt-OutList"></div><h2><a id="column-5" name="column-5"></a>5. National Opt-Out List</h2><p>France does not operate a national opt-out list for postal marketing. However, the Robinson-Stop list (only available in French <a href="https://www.service-public.fr/particuliers/vosdroits/R24281" target="_blank">here</a>), operated by the French Union of Direct and Digital Marketing ('UFMD'), identifies individuals who do not want to receive postal marketing. This list is shared with the UFMD's members who commit to respect the opt-out wishes of individual (the Postal and Telephone Marketing Guidance).</p><div name="6.Penalties" data-unique="6.Penalties"></div><h2><a id="column-6" name="column-6"></a>6. Penalties</h2><p><strong>National law</strong></p><p>Organisations that collect individual's personal details for the purposes of postal marketing through a fraudulent, disloyal or unlawful means can be subjected to a maximum of five years' imprisonment and a maximum fine of €300,000 (or €1.5 million for legal persons) (Articles 226-18 of the Penal Code and the Postal Mail Guidance).</p><p>Organisations that use details of an individual who has opted-out for marketing purposes are liable to maximum five years' imprisonment and a maximum fine of €300,000 (or €1.5 million for legal persons) (Article 226-18-1 of the Penal Code).</p><p>A fine of €750 (or €3,750 for legal persons) may be issued for each message sent to an individual who has opted-out from receiving such marketing in accordance with their rights under Article R10(4) of the Communications Code (the Post Q&amp;As and the Postal Mail Guidance).</p><p><strong>GDPR</strong></p><p>The infringement of Article 21 of the GDPR may lead to an administrative fine of up to €20 million or, in the case of an undertaking, up to 4% of the total worldwide annual turnover of the preceding financial year, whichever is higher (Article 83(5) of the GDPR, Article 20 of the Data Protection Act, and the Post Q&amp;As).</p><p>The infringement of other obligations under the GDPR may lead to the imposition of additional administrative fines, in line with Article 83 of the GDPR.</p></div></div></div>